so I'm working from those as the starting point for the doubling operation.\n\nThe third configuration change involves journal compression—currently defaulting to snappy but needing to switch to zlib. Since journal compression is a persistent storage engine setting, changing it requires a rolling restart of the MongoDB pods. I'll need to update the ConfigMap with all three changes (verbosity, threshold, and compression), mount it in the StatefulSet, and then trigger the restart to apply the new journal compression setting.\n\nHowever, there's a complication: the StatefulSet is currently using command-line arguments for settings like auth and keyFile, so I need to ensure all those existing arguments get migrated into the config file to avoid losing any configuration when I switch to using the mounted ConfigMap.\n\nThe plan is straightforward: update the ConfigMap with the new verbosity and slowOpThresholdMs values, mount it in the StatefulSet, change the command to reference the config file instead of individual flags, and perform a rolling restart. For maintaining availability during the update, I'll rely on the existing rolling update strategy and process the secondary replicas before the primary. I'll mount the ConfigMap as a volume at `/etc/mongod/` so the file appears at `/etc/mongod/mongod.conf`, then update the command to reference that path. The StatefulSet's existing `RollingUpdate` strategy will automatically trigger the rolling restart when I update the spec.\n\nSince journal compression requires a restart anyway, I'll update the ConfigMap with all the settings (verbosity, slowms, and journalCompressor), update the StatefulSet to mount and use the config file, and let the rolling restart apply everything at once. Writing the StatefulSet config... Writing the patch JSON...\n\nI need to think through the rolling update sequence carefully. When I patch the StatefulSet with the new command and volume configuration, Kubernetes will restart the pods in reverse order—starting from the highest index and working down—waiting for each one to be ready before moving to the next.\n\nSince Pod 0 is the primary and gets restarted last, the cluster maintains availability throughout the process. When Pod 0 finally restarts, it becomes a secondary and the remaining four pods elect a new primary among themselves. With five total members, I only need three running to maintain quorum, so this approach is safe.\n\nI should also apply the dynamic settings—the increased log verbosity and slower operation threshold—to all running pods immediately before starting the rolling restart. That way the settings take effect right away, and if the restart process takes time, they're already in place. The key constraint is that with a rolling update taking down one pod at a time, quorum is always maintained as long as at least three members stay online.\n\nFor the WiredTiger journal compressor setting, this takes effect at startup. When a pod restarts with zlib compression configured, MongoDB will use zlib for new journal entries while gracefully handling any existing journal files that used a different compressor. The rolling restart ensures each instance gets restarted to pick up this storage engine configuration change.\n\nNow I'm ready to execute the plan. I need to reconcile what the actual running state is versus what the ConfigMap specifies. The pods are currently using defaults since they don't mount the config file yet—so verbosity is 1, slowms is 100, and journalCompressor is snappy. The ConfigMap that was created as a reference has the target values, but I need to clarify whether the slowms target should be 200 or 400 based on what the current value actually is.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2366,"cache_read_input_tokens":38719,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2366},"output_tokens":21,"service_ti